Still yesterday morning I was fully convinced that getting up before 8 AM just isn't for me, but maybe it's possible to get used to it after all?&nbsp;Even in the winter?&nbsp;Because yesterday it took me a full hour to get my brain working at all after I got to the workplace just a few minutes after eight, whereas today I've been fully functional almost from the minute I reached my desk and woke up the PC. Maybe I just got so thoroughly in vacation mode over the past week or so... although to be honest I've never been good at waking up early, never ever, no matter what time&nbsp;I go to bed. But. It's actually nice to be at the office a bit earlier than usual because then I also get to leave a bit earlier, and now that aigha&quot;&gt;'s evening lessons haven't started yet we've been walking with the dogs in the evenings.&nbsp;&nbsp;

Oddly enough, this week I've also been enjoying work again even though it's been pretty busy -- not insanely busy but busy nonetheless. Maybe the vacation was just what I&nbsp;needed...?&nbsp;I've got a lot done, and am actually looking forward to getting my hands on some of the stuff still waiting for its turn. Whaaa... what's&nbsp;actually happening to me? 

I wish I&nbsp;could also enjoy writing again, but am trying to plod on whether or not it's fun. Here's to hoping it will feel even moderately good some day yet. 

Uhh, and now back to work-work once more!&nbsp;

[crossposted from Dreamwidth]

Original characters, no warnings at least at this point. This stuff is a totally unedited draft - I'm posting this as I go, just to make sure that I won't simply bury it on some memory stick and forget all about it (as I've been doing a lot recently).

If by some miracle anyone is reading, comments are very much appreciated.

This is getting so damn long that LJ told me it can't go on as a single post... so I'm continuing it <a href="http://quatorze.livejournal.com/629069.html">right here</a>. 

<lj-cut text="Harrosch, the story begins">=======

Cranberry has been a bit stiff today, but by now he's warming up and getting really pliant. I smell sweat and feel how his neck radiates heat to my hands even through leather gloves. I think we're getting close now.

&quot;Five feet.&quot;

Yes, that's Derien's voice. I tighten the left rein and shift my seat and Cranberry curves to the left underneath me while I listen to Derien to get the circle right; not too big, not too small. I think we've done pretty well today because we get back to the track right next to Derien. 

Cranberry snorts, pulls the reins a little but then settles once more to a steady walk. 

&quot;That's enough now&quot;, says the instructor. &quot;Well done, Harrosch, you're really getting the hang of this.&quot;

Triumphant, I wipe sweat from my face as Derien comes to grip the reins and walk beside Cranberry while we cool down.

&quot;How're you feeling?&quot; he asks.

&quot;Great,&quot; I tell him. &quot;How did it look?&quot; 

&quot;It looked good. I think Cranberry is just the horse for you.&quot; Derien pats the horse's neck. &quot;He's not too lazy nor too jumpy. Just right for you.&quot;

I settle to the sway of Cranberry's step, realizing I'm a bit out of breath. 

&quot;You know, I still can't believe how lucky you were that you didn't hurt yourself any worse when you fell off The Challenger,&quot; Derien says. 

&quot;But I didn't,&quot; I remind him. That one gave me a good fright, I still remember panicking when the fall knocked all wind out of my lungs and for a moment I couldn't breathe, but it's no use dwelling on it any more. &quot;Better forget about it, just you make sure mum or dad never hear about it.&quot;

&quot;I swear they won't,&quot; Derien says with emphasis. &quot;They'd never let me within a hundred feet from you!&quot; 

&quot;They would,&quot; I argue even though I know he's at least half right. 

After a few rounds the instructor tells me it's time to call it a day, and I slide down from the saddle. Cranberry gets his accustomed piece of bread from my pocket and then the stablehand walks him in, hooves clattering on stone floor. I wait while Derien goes to let Keren loose of the fence where he's been tied during my riding lesson, and soon he's pressing against my leg once more. Keren's always a bit worried to watch me on one of those animals that are even bigger than himself, and spends a while sniffing my hands and legs just to make sure I'm all right. I scratch him behind one ear and wait until he's satisfied, then grip the short leash attached to his collar.

&quot;Ready to go?&quot; 

&quot;Yes, let's,&quot; Derien says, and we walk out of the stable yard and into the park. There's a wet smell hanging in the air although it hasn't been raining today; the smell of autumn. I like it, and so does Keren who's eagerly breathing in all the scents even as he keeps a steady pace right there next to my leg.

It's not a long way to Derien's home, and that's of course where we go first. I need to change, it won't do to go home smelling of horse and hay and manure, although I'm getting tired of trying to keep this from my parents. I just know they'll have a fit when they find out. 

As I wash my face and hands I can't help thinking once again what a good thing it is that his parents and mine have somehow never felt the need to get to know each other. Maybe it's the difference in age or status or something else I can't understand? My parents are so much older, and I know we're also quite a bit wealthier, not that his family would be really poor or anything. As things are, his family thinks that my parents know about our escapades, and my parents are happy that I have at least this one friend. They probably imagine that we just stay indoors while he reads me or teaches me stuff, like when we're at my home. 

Little do they know, and it's best they don't. I dry my face, comb my hair thoroughly and tie it back once again, change into the clothes I went out in. Must be careful, Mum can be rather too observant sometimes and I don't want to ruin everything by forgetting something stupid like a sock or a glove. 

Keren has been sitting patiently outside the bathroom door and together we return to Derien's room. 

&quot;Do I look right?&quot; I ask him. 

&quot;Yes, you're good to go &ndash; no, wait, damnit.&quot; Derien comes closer. &quot;There's still something on the side of your neck, let me...&quot;

He rubs my neck with something moist, probably his own towel, and I have to bite my lip when his fingers accidentally touch bare skin. It gives me this little jolt, again. 

&quot;There, now it's gone.&quot;

&quot;What was it?&quot; I ask when he takes his hand away. 

&quot;I'm not sure, looked like horse spit.&quot; Derien grins. &quot;You must've got it on your sleeve when you were feeding that bread to Cranberry. Now you're all right, let's go so your Mum won't scold me too much.&quot;

&quot;Is it very late then?&quot; Should've been listening to the clock on the wall more carefully. 

&quot;No, not quite four yet, but it'll be a while before we get there. Come on.&quot;

&quot;Yes, let's go.&quot;

Keren pushes against me so that my fingers easily find the leash. The chorus of Derien's younger sisters and brothers and their mother saying their bye-byes is still ringing in my ears as we walk down the stairs and turn towards my home. 

&quot;I can't believe how well you ride already,&quot; Derien says as we stop to wait for a break in the flow of carriages and carts that fills the streets. This is not the busiest part of Deleon but not too far from it, either, and that shows in the traffic. &quot;You know, maybe you ought to tell your parents some time soon. I think they'd be proud to see you on horseback.&quot;

&quot;They'd be frightened out of their senses, more likely,&quot; I say and can't help snorting. &quot;But you're right, I guess I should. I just don't know how to do it.&quot;

A policeman watching over the crossing blows into his horn and Derien nudges my arm. &quot;Let's go across now.&quot; 

We reach the curb on the other side, then just a few dozen steps and we turn into another, smaller park. It's funny how different these trees sound than the older, bigger ones in the City Park where the stables are. 

&quot;Do you really think they might say you can't meet me any more?&quot; Derien asks after a while. 

I think about it for a few moments, listening to our steps on the fine gravel of the path.

&quot;I'm not sure. I wish I knew.&quot;

We don't talk very much after that, just walk on until we reach the right street and are just a stone's throw from my home. There I stop and Derien stops as well.

&quot;What is it?&quot;

I try, I really try to say it, but once again my courage fails me at the last moment. 

&quot;I just,&quot; desperately trying to grope for something else to say, &quot;I, uh, do you think you could ask your teacher if there's any way to get a school diploma even without attending the lessons?&quot;

Damn. I just can't bring myself to say it, not now. Sure, this is another thing I've been thinking about a lot, but not the question I wanted to ask. 

&quot;Sure I will!&quot; Derien is delighted. &quot;Why haven't you said so before? I'll ask him as soon as I see him tomorrow.&quot;

&quot;Great.&quot; I force a smile and walk swiftly on. &quot;I hope he says yes, because that'd really give Mum and Dad something to think about!&quot;

Luckily Derien doesn't notice anything, or maybe he's just being nice, but in any case he comes with me to our house without a comment. At the front door he squeezes my arm, we say our goodbyes and then he runs down the few steps while I go in and close the door behind me. 

&quot;I'm home, Mum!&quot;

&quot;There you are at last, Harrosch darling, I was getting really worried already!&quot; 

Oh, if only she didn't always sound so... so accusing and overly bright at the same time. 

&quot;Whatever for, Mum?&quot; The note of irritation creeps into my voice, I can't help it. &quot;You knew that me and Derien went out together, and that I'd come home for dinner.&quot;

I go to the stairs and begin climbing them up to my room, but her voice reaches me halfway there. 

&quot;Yes, yes, of course I knew, but I just can't help worrying, anything could happen &ndash;&quot;

&quot;Anything could happen to anybody, anywhere, anytime!&quot; Somehow I still haven't yelled at her, not once, although it's getting so difficult that I feel like someone was strangling me. &quot;I wish you'd understand that I'm not a baby any more!&quot;

Safely in my own room again, I lay down on the floor and bury my face in arms. Keren nuzzles me, questioning, then lets out a resigned sigh and settles down next to me. 

&quot;What would I do without you?&quot; I whisper to him. It's a miracle of sorts that I have him in the first place, a dog in our tidy house and such a huge, scruffy thing, too.

Keren says nothing, just licks my ear and his long muzzle settles more comfortably on my arm.

By dinnertime I've calmed down enough to go downstairs and take my own seat by the table. Behind me I hear Keren's sigh as he settles at the doorway, his hulk safely on the good side of the threshold, to wait for the maid to emerge with his bowl. 

The dinner is some steak with potatoes and broccoli, and Mum just has to butt in as I pile the broccoli on my plate. 

&quot;Darling, that's &ndash;&quot;

&quot;Mum, please!&quot; She's been the same for ever but somehow it's all getting more and more on my nerves these days, and it's also getting more difficult to just shrug it off. Nowadays I can feel my hackles rising almost as soon as I'm outside my room, and I've grown tired of biting my tongue all the time. &quot;I know how much I've taken, and yes, I am going to eat it all because I happen to like broccoli, as you should well know.&quot; 

&quot;Harrosch, I'm surprised at you!&quot; Dad says. &quot;Is that how Derien talks to his mother, or where have you learned to behave like that?&quot; 

&quot;No it's not,&quot; I say through clenched teeth. Of course they would have to drag him into this. &quot;But then his mother doesn't treat him like he was still barely six years old.&quot;

I dig into my food, hands shaking a little. Mercifully neither of the parents says anything. Dad is probably hungry and doesn't want to spoil the dinner, and Mum&hellip; well, Mum is of course miserable and upset about my bad behavior and doesn't really know what to do or say when I'm being so 'mean', like she says. 

No doubt they'll just ignore it, like they always do, and pretend that nothing ever happened. And I'll be bored to death, like I always am, although just about anything would be better than this playacting. We are all pretending that nothing is the matter and yet nobody is happy. They aren't happy with me because I'm not the shy and scared little boy I used to be. I'm not happy because I feel all the time that that's what I should be &ndash; though to please them or for some other reason entirely, I don't know. 

Dinner over, we go to the living room where Dad reads alound some stuff from the newspaper and then Mum reads another chapter of this month's book. It doesn't interest me too much, and I know I'm fidgeting by the time the clock strikes eight and I can legitimately get up from my chair and go to the hall to get Keren's leash. Dad follows me as always, he's still pulling on his coat when I open the front door and feel the bite of a cold breeze on my face. 

&quot;Do be careful, Harrosch darling!&quot; Mum calls after me. I walk down the stairs without a word and turn left, towards the small park, but don't get five steps before Dad has caught up with me and falls in pace with me and Keren. Surprisingly, he doesn't say anything for several moments.

&quot;Did you have a good time with Derien today?&quot; he asks at length, when I stop at the edge of the park and let Keren loose to stroll on the lawn. 

&quot;Yes.&quot;

&quot;That's good to hear.&quot; Dad pauses, clearly not knowing what to say next. &quot;You &ndash; you've just been rather irritable lately, and I thought maybe something has happened.&quot;

&quot;Like what?&quot; I ask. This is a surprise for sure. Dad talking to me like a real person? 

&quot;Yes, that maybe you've quarreled with him. Or that maybe his schoolwork has suffered because you spend so much time together.&quot;

I have to gasp. And here I was thinking for a moment that my parents might begin to understand!

&quot;Suffered? How exactly does it hurt that he's doing his homework with me?&quot;

&quot;Well, of course it's not as if...&quot; Dad checks himself but does it a little too late. Blood rushes to my ears, my heart is beating so hard that my temples hurt, and damn if only I dared run away, I'd do it right now. Rage grips my throat so hard it's difficult to breathe. 

&quot;Of course it isn't. How could I possibly help him, or study with him, because I don't have a brain?&quot; I swallow hard a few times but the tightness in my throat doesn't want to go away. &quot;Well don't you worry, Dad, I promise not to hurt his grades! And just so you know, if I'm not talking to you or Mum, it sure isn't his fault.&quot;

&quot;I didn't mean it like that,&quot; he says. 

&quot;Then what were you going to say?&quot; I challenge. &quot;It's not as if &ndash; what? It's not as if I could help him with his homework anyway?&quot;

&quot;Well...&quot;

I've heard enough. 

&quot;I can find my way home on my own,&quot; I say tightly. &quot;Keren knows the way.&quot;

&quot;Harrosch, what is the matter with you?&quot;

I walk on, far more slowly than I'd like, until we reach the crossing of paths where I need to turn left and start heading home. Dad follows me, I hear the rattle of his steps some ways behind me, but doesn't try to speak to me anymore as we finally return home and I go up to my room without a word. 

They're talking about me, I can hear the ever so faint murmur of voices from downstairs on my way to the bathroom and back, but won't even try to listen in. When I'm safely in bed, Keren comes to check on me and then settles right next to it. I let my left arm sag over the edge and scratch the rough hair on his neck, the other forearm thrown across my eyes to stop the tears of frustration and anger that are trying to well up. 

My useless eyes. Why is it that with my parents around I'm all the time so aware of being somehow defective, even though I don't even know exactly what I'm missing?

* * *

The next day feels like an eternity. Derien has a normal school day again, after the short one when we always go riding, and I hide in my room. I don't say a single extra word to my parents over breakfast, and after Dad has gone to work I hide in my room for the better part of the day, only going down to let Keren out to our little back yard once. I don't want to be around Mum and listen to her desperate efforts to find something to say to me. 

The clock chimes downstairs. One o'clock. Half past. Two o'clock. Half past. Three o'clock. Half &ndash; and right then, at last, I hear the knocker on the front door. But when I reach the top of the stairs, the door is closing again.

&quot;Mum?&quot;

&quot;Oh, you're awake, darling!&quot; She sounds far too breezy. &quot;I thought you were asleep.&quot;

&quot;Was that Derien right now?&quot;

Mum hesitates. 

&quot;What did you tell him?&quot; I shout. &quot;Why didn't you let him in?&quot;

&quot;I &ndash;&quot;

&quot;I hate you!&quot; In my agitation I nearly slip on the stairs but catch a hold of the railing with both hands, push Mum away as she frantically rushes to help me, and locate my coat. &quot;Come, Keren, side!&quot;

&quot;But Harrosch!&quot; Mum wails, I push her away again and tear the front door open. 

Keren is next to me, I don't waste time bothering to attach his leash before closing the door behind me and holding my breath to hear. &quot;Derien?&quot;

There's no reply. I grab the iron rail, it's freezing cold under ungloved hands but I don't care. &quot;Keren, let's go now!&quot; 

I'm alone. I'm not used to being all alone. Is the curb clear? I know how many steps it is until the corner, but my steps are shorter now and suddenly I'm not sure at all how far I am. I'm breathing hard and my hand on Keren's leash trembles, it unsettles him as well. Should I turn back after all? Is there anyone I can ask? 

Then there are steps, familiar steps, and they're coming from ahead &ndash; not from behind me. &quot;Harrosch? I thought I heard you!&quot; Derien sounds breathless and smiling. &quot;Hey, what's the matter? You mum said you weren't feeling all right.&quot;

&quot;I'm not,&quot; I say and swallow hard a few times to quell the sudden panic. &quot;Can we go somewhere?&quot;

&quot;Sure,&quot; he says. He's coming straight from school to do his homework with me, the backpack is there slung over a shoulder as he turns to walk next to me, arm brushing against mine. &quot;What's going on?&quot; 

&quot;Not here,&quot; I say, but before we get two steps further I hear it: the front door opens. Our front door. Derien hears it, too, and stops.

&quot;Your mother is there,&quot; he says. &quot;Should we go &ndash;&quot;

&quot;Just tell her we're going to your home. I'm not going back now.&quot;

&quot;...okay.&quot; He turns around, voice clear and confident. &quot;It's all right, Harrosch and I are going to my place!&quot; 

She doesn't say anything and I tug on Derien's arm. &quot;Let's go now.&quot;

&quot;Alright, alright!&quot; 

He doesn't ask anything and we walk briskly, side by side, stopping every now and then to give Keren some welcome time off. Derien's talking about his school day, what they've been doing, what kind of homework he's got, and I envy him in silence. Some friends of his walk along the street, I recognize some of their voices and they stop for a moment to talk to us. I've met at least three of them before, not that I could say that I really know anyone. When we go about it's mostly just the three of us, Derien and me and Keren. Derien's classmates and neighbors say hello to us but they rarely come to talk. I'm sure it's because of me; my presence puts them off. It seems to put off most everybody. 

Derien's family have got used to me, though, and that's feels always as incredible. Why haven't my parents, although they've lived with me much longer? We retreat to his room, a luxury he's entitled to as the eldest child with the most homework, and he spreads out his books. 

&quot;What've you got for today?&quot; I ask.

&quot;Some algebra, geography, history&hellip; geometry, civics, literature. Oh, and an essay to write, but I won't have to turn it in until next week so I'll do that later.&quot; Derien settles more comfortably on the bed next to me. &quot;What would you like to start with? Algebra?&quot;

&quot;Let's do the boring stuff first,&quot; I suggest.

&quot;Suits me fine. Or&hellip; would you rather talk first?&quot; 

I bite my lip. &quot;No, let's do the homework.&quot;

So we tackle the mathematics first. That's the toughest stuff for me to get a grip of, not so much geometry but the other things. Then onwards to more interesting topics, Derien reads the chapters for me and then we ponder together how to answer the questions his teacher has given them to answer, finishing with my favorite subject: history. Derien loves to repeat to me the fascinating stories with which his history teacher always delights his class, and I love listening to them. How I'd want to hear them for myself. 

&quot;But hey, you wanted me to ask my teacher!&quot; Derien sits up, clearly excited. &quot;I did ask, and he was pretty sure it could be arranged but he'd love to talk to you first. Harrosch, do you think you could come to school with me one of these days?&quot;

The question takes my breath away. The thought scares me more than I'd want to admit to myself, it scares me to the core, but isn't this something I've been dreaming about for a long time now? I cannot say no &ndash; but saying yes means having to tell my parents. 

Derien shifts a little closer to me. &quot;Hey, what is it? What's the matter? Why did your Mum say you weren't feeling alright?&quot;

I don't know where to start, and he settles down once more on the bed beside me. 

&quot;Tell me, Harrosch. I'm sure we can figure out something together, if I just know what's going on.&quot;

&quot;I wish I could explain,&quot; I start and then stop to grope for words. &quot;I mean, it's been the same ever since we first me, hasn't it? That they worry and make a fuss and all that, and it's always been a pain in the neck &ndash; ever since you started taking me out and I realized that there's so much more in the world than I'd known, and that I might not have to just hear about it and try to understand, and... Yes, it's always been the same, but I wish I knew why it's now getting harder and harder to take it! I used to just say 'yes, Mum' and do stuff with you and never tell them, and everything was fine when they didn't know, but now all their fussing just makes me feel like &ndash; like my head will burst!&quot; 

&quot;I think they're having trouble understanding that you're not a little kid any longer,&quot; Derien says. He's warm, our bodies touching all the way from upper arm to shoulder and hip and leg, and I'd want to press closer but will not do that. &quot;You know, my Mum sometimes sighs and says how incredible it is that I'm in upper school already, that it feels like she was still changing my nappies not so many weeks ago.&quot;

&quot;Yes, and I'm their poor blind baby, too,&quot; I grind out. It feels like trying to eat sand. &quot;Can't remember how many times I've heard it, adults talking about it and lamenting it and wondering what will come of me, poor child, commiserating with my parents... As if I was deaf, too, and totally brainless, and couldn't understand a word they're saying!&quot;

&quot;You know what?&quot; Derien puts an arm around my shoulders. &quot;We'll go there together. I'll come with you today, and we tell them what we've been doing. That we've been studying together, and the riding and canoeing, and going to see my teacher tomorrow.&quot; 

I huddle closer to him, swallowing tears. He's right. I don't know when I've changed so much and why my parents drive me so mad these days, but clearly things aren't going back to what they used to be. I want to be able to breathe again.

&quot;Let's do it,&quot; I whisper. 

We don't really talk while walking back to my home. It's a bit later than usual, there's even more traffic all around and I can't help sticking a bit closer to Derien. I'm nervous, there's no denying it, and the closer we get the more I'm on edge. I don't really know what to expect. A talk? A row? One thing's for certain: my parents are going to be upset and shocked. 

When we enter the house, Mum is fluttering even more nervously than normally. For a moment I'm at a loss before I remember what happened earlier and how I left the house. Doing homework with Derien has driven the memory away for a few moments, it now feels like it'd happened a long time ago.

&quot;Is Dad home yet?&quot; I ask. 

&quot;Yes, darling &ndash;&quot;

I hear Dad come from the direction of the living room. 

&quot;Harrosch?&quot; He comes to the hall and stops. &quot;Thank goodness you're there! Where have you been this late? Your mother was getting really worried about you!&quot;

That's a lie. They both have, and I can't understand why he should try to blame it only on her. 

&quot;I really wish you wouldn't,&quot; I say curtly and take a deep breath. This is it now. I'd want to escape to my room but there's something else I need to do first. &quot;I... I think we need to talk about something.&quot; 

&quot;What is it?&quot; Dad is completely nonplussed but Derien comes to my aid.

&quot;Oh, we'd just need to go somewhere tomorrow and I promised Harrosch that I'd be there with him when he tells you,&quot; he says brightly. 

&quot;Right... well, let's go and sit down, shall we?&quot;

Derien comes to sit next to me on the small sofa. What would I do without him there? Keren, too, takes advantage of the situation and curls on the floor around my feet. 

&quot;So, what was this talk about going somewhere?&quot; Dad sounds businesslike. &quot;Don't you have school tomorrow, Derien?&quot;

&quot;I do,&quot; he says, &quot;but that's just the point.&quot;

&quot;What then?&quot;

Derien nudges my arm.

&quot;I'm going there with him,&quot; I say. &quot;I want to talk to his classroom teacher about maybe taking some exams at some point. And &ndash; and about going to school, too.&quot;

That last addition is something that just slips out. My words are followed by a stunned silence and then something worse. 

&quot;What are you talking about?&quot; Dad asks at the same moment with Mum's &quot;Poor darling, how could you go to school?&quot; 

&quot;I can walk!&quot; I explode. &quot;That's how other people go there! And I'm not deaf or mute or completely stupid, either, although you never seem to understand it. I remember things I've heard, believe it or not, and I have learned quite a lot when we've done homework with Derien.&quot;

&quot;I asked my teacher about this,&quot; Derien puts in, &quot;and he said he'd very much like to meet Harrosch and talk about this in person. We could go there together in the morning, and I can then walk home with Harrosch when we have sports at noon, I'm sure the teacher will let me skip the first half an hour or so.&quot;

&quot;But... I still don't understand,&quot; Dad says. &quot;To school? Harrosch?&quot;

&quot;Yes.&quot; My voice is trembling, I can hear it, but at least I'm not screaming my head off like I'd want to. &quot;I'll be going there tomorrow morning with Derien, and I'll tell you then what the teacher says.&quot;

They don't know what to say. I can feel the worry radiating from them like heat from a fireplace and it makes me want to pull away. That heat has been there all my life and even though it used to be good, nowadays it's too warm, too suffocating. Too close. 

&quot;Maybe I ought to come along,&quot; Mum says weakly. 

&quot;No!&quot; I sit straighter. &quot;Mum, try to get it. I'm not a baby anymore! I don't need you to hold my hand all the damn time. I'm going to be just fine with Derien.&quot;

&quot;I made sure that Keren can come along as well,&quot; Derien adds, &quot;and the teacher said he's welcome.&quot; 

&quot;I guess... I guess there's nothing else to do but say yes, then,&quot; Dad says. &quot;But Harrosch, why are you like this? Haven't we done enough for you? Why are you so &ndash; &quot;

&quot;You've done quite enough,&quot; I burst out. &quot;And then some, and then some. You pamper and worry and look after me, and I think you'd be happiest if I never ever went out of the door except with you holding my both hands so that I couldn't do a single thing without you. But guess what? Maybe that was alright when I really was a baby, but I'm almost seventeen now and I want to do things by myself. I want to be able to do things by myself, and that's something you've never even tried to teach me!&quot;

&quot;But &ndash; but,&quot; Mum exclaims. &quot;Does this mean that Derien's not looking after you when you're out together?&quot;

&quot;Of course I look after him!&quot; Derien huffs, indignant and with good reason, too. &quot;When we go out on the street I look out for traffic, and warn him about curbs and stuff, but I don't need to do that for every step.&quot;

&quot;You know why I don't want to go out anymore with you, Mum?&quot; I put in. &quot;It's because you're never quiet. You babble and babble and talk so that I can't keep track or hear where we are and where we're going, and I can't take it!&quot;

&quot;Harrosch darling,&quot; Mum begins but Dad cuts her off.

&quot;No, let him talk.&quot; He sighs and the chair rustles underneath him. &quot;Please go on, Harrosch. I want to know what it is that you are saying.&quot;

&quot;I'm saying,&quot; I start and have to stop to take a deep breath. The thought that they might finally listen to me is overwhelming. &quot;I'm saying that being blind doesn't mean I'm completely helpless, and that I really wish you'd understand it. I know there are lots of things I'll never be able to do, but there's also a lot that I can do if I just get the chance, and... and you need to give me that chance.&quot;

&quot;So, what kind of things have you been doing with Derien? In addition to studying, that is?&quot;

Dad sounds neutral. I'm not sure if I quite trust him, but there's only one way to find out. 

&quot;We've been canoeing,&quot; I say and hear Mum's gasp. &quot;Along the canals in Crescent Park.&quot;

&quot;Oh, I used to like that when I was a boy.&quot; Dad's voice is somehow muted. 

&quot;We also go running quite often,&quot; Derien adds. &quot;And Harrosch runs pretty fast! That's something Keren especially loves, too.&quot;

At my feet, Keren raises his head and his tail wags a couple of times at the mention of his name. 

&quot;Running?&quot; Mum sounds like she's close to tears.

&quot;Yes, running. Derien just keeps sure the path is clear.&quot;

Dad sighs again. &quot;So, what time are you leaving tomorrow morning?&quot;

I'm stunned into silence.

&quot;The class starts at nine, but I thought it might be a good idea to get there a bit early, so... around eight?&quot;

&quot;Alright, that means then that we'll see each other in the morning when you come to pick Harrosch up,&quot; Dad says. 

&quot;Yes, sir!&quot; Derien squeezes my arm and jumps up. &quot;I think I'll need to go home now, they're expecting me for dinner soon. I'll be here at eight tomorrow, Harrosch!&quot; 

&quot;I'll be ready,&quot; I promise.

When the front door closes once more after him, I turn to clim the stairs to my room but Dad has followed me to the hall. 

&quot;Harrosch, won't you come back to the living room?&quot; 

&quot;All right.&quot; 

I know he's there, but instead of coming to guide me by the hand he waits until I reach the door and navigate back to the sofa on my own. Mum is sniffling as Dad goes and sits down next to her.

&quot;Now, what if we all try to stay calm and reasonable?&quot; he says. &quot;And please stop crying, dear. I'm sure no one is saying that we wouldn't have tried our best, but it seems that perhaps we've been trying too hard. Or maybe we've been doing the wrong things?&quot;

&quot;I know you mean well,&quot; I say. Of course they do. Of course they only want my best. That's the damnedest part of it. If they didn't, I wouldn't need to feel this guilty for getting so angry when they do the things they do. &quot;But please stop trying to do everything for me. You can't. Nobody can. I want to find out for myself what I can do and where I need help, I want to do things and not just hear about them!&quot;

&quot;I just can't help thinking about all the dangers,&quot; Mum says. Her voice is quavering. &quot;When you can't see around... I remember, when you were a toddler, how you were always banging yourself into things and getting hurt, poor child, before we realized what was wrong.&quot;

I cringe. &quot;Mum, if there's one word I never ever want to hear again, it's that one &ndash; poor. I'm not 'poor' anything! I just cannot see, whatever that really means.&quot;

&quot;Now, now,&quot; Dad cuts in. &quot;Let's focus on the here and now, shall we? So you're going to school tomorrow with Derien? Did you really mean that you might be able to start going to school?&quot;

&quot;I don't know. I hope so. Why have I never been to any school?&quot; I ask, because this is something I've often wondered about. I remember asking my parents, too, but the answer has always been the same: it's not possible because I'm blind. Well, I'm not going to be satisfied with that any longer. 

&quot;That's what they told us, back when you were little,&quot; Dad says. &quot;That they wouldn't be able to take you in because you'd need too much looking after and they already had so many children at the school. We couldn't quite afford hiring a teacher to home-school you at the time, and we also didn't want to put you in any special school for the blind because the only ones we could find out about were boarding schools. And rather expensive, too.&quot; 

My shoulders slump. I don't think I would've liked that, either, and besides, then I most probably would've never met Derien and his uncle and Keren, who back then was still hardly more than a puppy. 

&quot;But it's really wonderful that you get to talk to this teacher,&quot; Dad continues and I finally begin to believe him. &quot;You must tell us everything about it, especially what he says about taking the exams.&quot;

Mum hardly says a word until bedtime, whereas I can tell that Dad is genuinely trying to act differently. The usual evening walk with Keren is different, too: at first Dad takes my arm, as usual, but after a while he pulls a little away and then just walks beside me in silence. When I stop and loosen Keren's leash, Dad chuckles.

&quot;You know we are at the right spot, don't you? How do you do it?&quot;

I must think about it for a moment. &quot;I know how many steps we've walked, and what the pavement feels, and how the sounds echo. And of course I can smell the park. Besides, Keren knows where we're going.&quot;

&quot;It seems like a miracle,&quot; he says softly. &quot;You know, all those are things I've never come to think about, because I can see where I'm going. But then I always knew that your hearing is extraordinary, noticed it already when you were nothing but a child.&quot;

&quot;I've tried to imagine what it's like to see,&quot; I say quietly. &quot;But I can't, really. I just know that it'd be useful and would make many things easier.&quot;

&quot;Such as canoeing,&quot; Dad says.

&quot;Yes.&quot; I hesitate for a moment and then add: &quot;Or riding.&quot;

Dad gasps. &quot;You... you cannot mean it, Harrosch. Riding? A horse? Have you &ndash; you haven't done it, have you?&quot;

&quot;What if I have?&quot; I take a few steps on the grass because Keren is pulling a little.

&quot;Oh my goodness. Oh for heaven's sake.&quot; Dad is quiet for a good while, then he says: &quot;Listen, Harrosch &ndash; let's not breathe a word about this to your mother. And please, please do be careful.&quot;

&quot;I'll try,&quot; I say and turn back towards his voice. &quot;Come on, Keren.&quot;

When I reach the path again, Dad takes my hand in his. I don't pull it away. 

 * * * *

&quot;You're quiet, Harrosch.&quot;

I stop to and loosen Keren's leash a bit. &quot;I'm pretty tired. Never realized one could get this tired from just talking to people and being around them.&quot; 

&quot;Oh, right. I was afraid you'd be disappointed or something,&quot; Derien says.

&quot;Disappointed?&quot; I turn more towards him. &quot;Why would I be disappointed?&quot;

&quot;Well, you know, because it's not quite so simple after all. The exams and all that.&quot;

&quot;I don't mind. Not at all,&quot; I say firmly. &quot;The main thing is that I'll be able to do it eventually, and maybe even go to some lessons as well. Right now I'm awfully happy to have been promised that much!&quot;

Yes, I really am. It's noon, Derien is walking home with me, and I'm still trying to recover from the novel experience of being in the same room with two dozen people at the same time. I've met his classroom teacher and all of his classmates, as well as a few other teachers, and right now it's all just one big blur in my head. Everyone was curious and more than a little uncertain of how they should behave when I'm around, but in spite of a few awkward moments everything went smoothly enough. 

I've also had a long talk with the teacher who was interested and encouraging and welcoming. I do understand that my presence in the classroom would pose problems for teachers not used to dealing with blind people, but still the teacher &ndash; Master Nemeal, with a pleasant voice and long, cool hands &ndash; said he'd do everything in his power to make sure that I could start attending school at the beginning of next term. 

Just thinking about it makes me sizzle inside. To go there every day and meet all those people? It's going to be tough, no doubt about it, and yet I can hardly wait. It also means learning to navigate whole new areas and places and rooms and spaces, to recognize whole crowds of people... but no, I'm not going to be intimidated by all that. There's only one thing that worries me. 

&quot;Derien,&quot; I begin, &quot;I just hope that... that it won't be too tough on you.&quot;

&quot;What're you talking about?&quot; he asks, sounding genuinely puzzled.

&quot;Exactly that. I'll be relying on you so much, even more than so far.&quot;

&quot;As if I'd mind!&quot; Derien huffs. &quot;You're my best friend, and you know that!&quot;

&quot;Still. I also mean work.&quot; I chew my lip. &quot;I wish it wasn't so, but there's no way around it.&quot;

&quot;Don't you worry about that, Harrosch,&quot; Derien says firmly. &quot;I honestly don't mind. Besides, you're so clever that once you get the hang of school, you'll do better than anyone else in the class!&quot;

&quot;You wish...&quot;

But he insists he's right, and the rest of the walk is spent squabbling over which one of us is right. Too bad that Derien then has to return to school, I'd love to have him over for the afternoon to wait for Dad to come from work because I know things are going to be really awkward with just Mum around. 

When I go in, though, there's a surprise waiting for me: Dad is already home. At this hour? 

&quot;I told them I had something very important and had to take the afternoon off,&quot; he explains. &quot;Well, now, let's sit down for lunch and hear about your day!&quot;

It's oddly heart-warming that he should be so interested, although of course it also feels weird after all this time when they've just assumed so many things and decided stuff over my head. At the same time I can't help thinking that maybe things would've been different if I'd just spoken out earlier. What if I had? Would it have made any difference? I can't know that for sure, but somehow I doubt it. Maybe I needed to build up all that anger for myself, in order to be assertive enough? Or maybe I'm just making up excuses for not doing this before.

Whatever, but all of a sudden I feel much more like a real person in my home. And there's also another surprise waiting for me, for Mum is also clearly trying to act differently. I think they must've had a talk with Dad at some point, for she's not babying me nearly as much as usual. Instead of doing things for me I notice that several times during lunch she actually talks to me and asks what I want or directs me to the right objects. 'To your left, Harrosch', or 'it's too far for you to reach, wait a moment, I'll hand it to you', instead of 'I put some of it on your plate already'.  

Still I feel we've come a long way in a single day, and that's better than I dared hope. Maybe I was a coward not to talk to my parents earlier, maybe I should've given them more credit, trusted them a littler more, but that's easy to say after the fact. In any case, now I know that things can change and I'm going to hold on to this. 

* * * * * * 

I should've known that this would happen for sure &ndash; of course exactly today, when I have someone to impress, Cranberry is being a bit cranky. It doesn't take long before I'm sweating just to keep him moving, but all things considered I think I'm doing a rather good job of it. And I must, too, because this is the first time Mum is here to watch and in fact Dad didn't tell her until this morning what my seventeenth birthday would be like. First a ride, then back home to change, and afterwards to dine out &ndash; yes, out, in a real restaurant, with my parents and of course Derien and two other boys from our class. 

Mum has been in shock ever since she was told, over breakfast, what the day's program would be. I got to say what we'd do today, and damn but it feels good. So good that I'm not going to let one horse spoil the moode, even though said horse has apparently decided to be lazy and sloppy today and needs frequent little kicks to keep properly awake! 

I'm so focused on riding that I nearly protest when the instructor tells me it's time to stop, and Derien jogs again to walk Cranberry while we're cooling down. He hasn't been riding today because of the sore he got in his leg in sports earlier this week, but he says that's just as well because now my parents have had the chance to watch just me. 

&quot;Is it really so late?&quot; I ask, still suspicious of how short the lesson has felt. 

&quot;Sure thing, about five minutes to go!&quot; Derien laughs, then lowers his voice. &quot;I bet your Mum is thinking that it's been far too long, you know. She looks petrified.&quot;

&quot;Oh, of course.&quot; She would be scared, no doubt about that. &quot;What about Dad?&quot;

&quot;He's proud of you,&quot; Derien says with a grin. &quot;On edge, sure, but so very proud as well that he's beaming.&quot;

I relax to Cranberry's pace and just enjoy myself until Derien walks him to the front of the stable. As soon as I'm standing on my own feet again, I hear steps behind me. It's my parents.

&quot;Harrosch, that was quite incredible!&quot; Dad actually comes and hugs me tight. &quot;I never thought you'd ride so well, I mean I imagined that someone would be there walking next to you all the time!&quot;

The riding instructor joins us as well. &quot;Of course we did that at first, but since we found such a suitable horse for him we've tried out this system and it works very nicely. There just needs to be someone to tell where exactly they are at any given time, but as you could see, they're working together just wonderfully.&quot;

For a moment I'm afraid that he might accidentally slip and say something about the mishap I had with The Challenger, but he's wiser than that. Mum manages a few weak words of agreement, Dad chats with the instructor for a little more, and then we head home. 

It has not been easy, oh no. Not easy for them to unlearn something they've spent fifteen years perfecting: how to look after their poor helpless blind baby so that he never needs to bump into anything, never needs to do anything for himself, never needs to be frustrated or hurt or lost. There's been just one thing they've always refused to think about &ndash; that they cannot always be there to do that. Or maybe I'm being unfair, most probably they have thought about that and then decided that it's too dreadful and pushed the scary notion away. 

Another thing that probably hasn't occurred to them at all is that I might not want them to be always there, always sheltering me and putting up a wall between me and the world. That I might want to feel the world for myself, even if it occasionally involves me getting my hands dirty or even hurting myself a bit. And that, even though I know I won't be able to make it on my own, I might not want them around all the time. That I might some day want someone else.

So these past few months have been one rough road for all of us. For me it has meant starting school at last, for them it's meant several hours a day when they haven't been able to hover around me. I know that especially Mum has found it hard to get used to having some time for herself, too, during the day. But we're all trying. Mum and Dad are trying not to baby me too much, I'm trying not to get too frustrated when they slip back to how things used to be &ndash; and also to accept that I'm going to need a lot of help, always. 

Going to school has really brought home to me how much I depend on others, and that's been one tough lesson to take. Another tough lesson is that people at large are not used to dealing with a blind person. Someone like me is supposed to stay at home, or if we go about it always happens with a minder who faces the world on our behalf. Thus, outside the familiar walls of home when my parents or Derien can't always be at hand, I'm still so damn lost that I keep getting angry at myself, not that it helps at all. Keren is there of course, but he's just a dog. A big and very clever dog, granted, but dogs aren't able to speak and cannot understand too complicated things.

As if he could hear my thoughts, Keren nudges my hand with his muzzle and I scratch his ear, almost ashamed. 'Just' a dog? There's nothing 'just' about Keren. He's a wonderdog. 

On the way home I keep hearing about how impressed my parents are by what they have witnessed at the stables, and that goes a long way to lift my mood again. Derien trots home to change before dinner while Dad pops into my room to help me get ready. Then it's out again, a short walk to the nearest street where the streetcars run, and a couple of stops later Derien joins us once more. He's excited as he slips to the seat next to me.

&quot;You know, I almost asked what's wrong when I noticed Keren's not there,&quot; he says, &quot;before I remembered where we're going!&quot;

&quot;It feels all weird that he's not there,&quot; I agree. &quot;But I suppose it wouldn't be alright to take him into the restaurant?&quot;

&quot;No, no,&quot; Dad says. &quot;Outdoor restaurants in summer, yes, but not to a place like this.&quot;

&quot;It's a very nice place,&quot; Mum puts in. Once again she sounds nervous. &quot;Quite in the city center, too, I'm sure there'll be quite a lot of people.&quot;

&quot;I've booked us a table so there's no reason to worry, anyway,&quot; Dad says. &quot;Now, we need to watch where we are. It's not many stops away any more.&quot;

I can hear the rattle of traffic around and my heart is beating faster; I've never really been to the city during the busiest times. And when we get off the streetcar, I'm hit by the noise created by more people I've ever encountered at a time &ndash; they just are there, I know it, and I grab Derien's arm hard. In response his hand slips into mine and our fingers entwine tight.

&quot;Don't worry, I won't let go,&quot; he says. &quot;Just walk right next to me, there's a lot of people around, quite some crowd.&quot;

&quot;I know.&quot; I try to breathe more slowly, ears pricked to cope with the multitude of sounds attacking me from every direction. &quot;Mum and Dad are in front of us, right?&quot;

&quot;Yes, darling, we're right here!&quot; Mum pipes in and Derien stops abruptly. &quot;Are you sure you're all right? Maybe we should've picked some other time &ndash;&quot;

&quot;Nothing wrong with me!&quot; It comes more sharply than I meant.

&quot;Let's just walk on, dear. We can't possibly walk side by side, all four of us, and it's better if Harrosch and Derien can follow us.&quot;

Indeed, the place isn't very far away and then I hear our friends' voices.

&quot;Hey, Harrosch, Derien, we're here!&quot; 

It's a relief to hear something familiar in the middle of the sea of sounds, and soon we stop next to them. My parents have met Karal and Rhomir before so there's no need for introductions before we enter the restaurant, a wholly new experience for me. 

Another wave of relief washes over me when I register the pleasant quiet. Yes, there are people talking, the clink of cutlery, steps and all that, but it's all nicely muted. A man comes to meet us at the door &ndash; the head waiter, Derien whispers to me &ndash; and Dad informs him that we have a reservation for six people. We are taken to our table and get to sit down, then the waiter goes around the table to hand us the menus. The presence of someone suddenly so close to me gives me a start.

&quot;I don't need it,&quot; I say a bit curtly.

&quot;Excuse me?&quot;

&quot;It's okay,&quot; Karal says easily, &quot;our friend's blind. Shall I read it for you, Harrosch?&quot;

&quot;I'm sorry, I wasn't aware...&quot; The waiter is clearly taken aback but Dad and Derien assure him everything's alright and he leaves us. Karal leans closer and begins to tell me what there's to choose from, and I relax again. 

&quot;Maybe we should switch places?&quot; Derien says. &quot;I mean, silly of us not to come to think of it, now you're sitting so that the waiters can walk behind you without you noticing it.&quot;

&quot;Hey, we can keep an eye, right?&quot; Karal suggests. &quot;He's between you and me anyway, so we'll act as guards here.&quot;

&quot;Yes, and I can see over your shoulder,&quot; Rhomir adds. &quot;I'll be an extra lookout. No worries, Harrosch, we'll make sure nobody sneaks up on you!&quot; 

I smile to them. Damn but it feels good to be around them. It's not just Derien anymore, now I also have others to rely on &ndash; like these two, my second best friends in class. 

&quot;Okay, but listen now, you need to pick your meal now! Shall I read the starters through once more?&quot; 

Not knowing half of the things on the menu makes things difficult and interesting, but finally I manage to take my pick and we place our order. It's all so exciting; what the place sounds and smells like, the quiet steps of waiters moving about, bits and pieces of conversation wafting from around us. The feel of different, heavier cutlery and glasses decorated by patterns cut into their surface. The taste of dishes the like of which I've never sampled before. Wine on my tongue. My friends talking and laughing, they don't take long to relax even in the more formal surroundings and with my parents around. 

It's an evening of great fun, the best birthday I've ever had. Eventually we leave the place, happy and just a little lightheaded though more for the fun we've had than for the few sips of wine, and a breeze from the outside touches my face. It's cooler and wetter than before; it must be evening. Rhomir and Derien come to walk with me, one on each side, arm in arm, and I hear Karall's confident steps right in front of me. 

&quot;There are lots of people still around,&quot; I say, surprised at the noises surrounding us.

&quot;Yeah, it's evening and there are many restaurants along this street,&quot; Karall says. &quot;That's why I'm walking right here, I'm the biggest of us and I promise to make sure nobody bumps into you!&quot;

&quot;Karall is our bouncer,&quot; Derien confirms. &quot;And he's doing a good job of it, too!&quot;

&quot;Hey, pretty boys, you're headed the wrong way!&quot; 

I don't recognize the voice from a bit further away, but I feel how both Derien and Rhomir turn that way. They don't stop, though, just keep walking on.

&quot;What was that?&quot; I ask them.

&quot;It's, umm...&quot; Derien is clearly embarrassed. Rhomir laughs a bit but I still hear the awkwardness.

&quot;I think those guys were headed for 'The Oasis', it's in this street corner near the place we're coming from,&quot; he says lightly and Karall adds: &quot;We saw it on our way here, you know.&quot;

&quot;What's 'The Oasis'?&quot; I ask.

&quot;It's a restaurant,&quot; Karall speaks at the same time with Rhomir's &quot;It's a club.&quot;

&quot;Right, but what's special about it? Why did they say we're going the wrong way?&quot; Their confusion just makes me more curious. 

&quot;It's a gay club,&quot; Derien says hastily, voice dropping.

&quot;Oh.&quot;

My face goes all hot. Here I am, walking arm in arm with two other boys. That must be why this someone shouted to us, and I'd want to pull myself free from them but cannot. 

We don't really talk anymore on our way to the nearby square where Dad says we can find a cab to take us all home. He's right, we all climb into a cab and drive off, and the steady clatter of the horse's hooves on the street nearly lulls us all into a half-dream. I thank my friends and say goodnight to them as we drop them off near their homes, then me and Dad take Keren out for an evening stroll.

When finally I get to bed, I'm tired but still take a long time to fall asleep. The day has been great, true, and yet that one voice keeps ringing in my ears. Headed the wrong way... 

I know what 'gay' means. And I suspect that I shouldn't feel the way I sometimes feel when I'm with Derien. 

* * * * * * 

It's been raining a little during the day, but thankfully not any more as we're walking home from school. There's a slight breeze, it makes the trees of the park whisper around us but that sound is just about drowned by the singing of birds. There are dozens if not hundreds of them, chattering and twittering and beeping each in their own voice to announce that it's spring and they are in a hurry. 

Keren keeps stopping abruptly, Derien tells me that's because he's staring at the birds rustling in the bushes we're walking past, and I laugh. Now I know what a small bird is like because I've held one of the stuffed birds that are kept on the glass shelves of the nature science class. A dead thing, but now I know not just its song but how tiny and fragile it is, and what its beak and feet and feathers feel like. They used to be just sounds for me before; not so any more. 

&quot;Hi, Derien!&quot; 

I know that voice. It's Nealla, a girl who lives a few houses away from Derien's home. We've met her quite a few times recently, usually on our way to or from school, because she goes to the girls' school and our paths cross in the park if we happen to be out and about at the same time. 

&quot;Hi,&quot; we both say in unison.

&quot;Oh, sorry, Harrosch, I didn't see you at first!&quot;

Am I imagining or did her tone change ever so slightly when she realized I'm there, too? 

&quot;Had a nice day at school?&quot; Derien asks her as she slows down her step to keep abreast of us. 

&quot;Ye-es, quite nice. We had an exam but I think I did rather well. How about your day?&quot;

&quot;An exam as well,&quot; Derien says. &quot;In history.&quot;

&quot;Was it hard?&quot; she asks.

&quot;Not too bad. And I bet Harrosch aced it anyway!&quot; He grins. &quot;Didn't you?&quot;

&quot;Well,&quot; I hedge, &quot;the teacher said it went pretty well.&quot;

&quot;He's just being modest,&quot; Derien informs her. &quot;He's quite the monster in history, Harrosch is.&quot;

We continue chatting, mostly about school, as we walk through the park and let Keren have some fun along the way. When the sounds of the street again grow louder, Derien stops. 

&quot;I need to walk Harrosch home now,&quot; he says. &quot;See you again, Nealla!&quot;

Before we reach the corner where we need to turn right, Derien turns a little. He doesn't stop or even falter in his step, but he does turn. To look at her? My throat feels tighter. 

&quot;I think you like her.&quot; It comes out lightly enough; good. 

&quot;What do you mean?&quot; Derien asks, just a touch too quickly.

&quot;Exactly that. I think you like her. Is she &ndash; pretty?&quot;

Not that I really know what that means, but I've heard it often enough.

&quot;Oh, quite pretty!&quot; His voice is nonchalant, and now I'm certain of it.

It feels a little like being hit with something very cold somewhere under the heart, like the touch of freezing iron, and the physical pain takes me by surprise. How is it possible that a thought can cause something so real? 

&quot;Sorry, did you stumble? Am I walking too fast?&quot; Derien sounds worried, I must've slowed down or something.

&quot;No, I was just careless, I guess.&quot; I tighten my hold of Keren's leash and focus on keeping my step steady. &quot;And maybe I'm a bit tired, too.&quot; 

&quot;Shouldn't have stayed up so late last night,&quot; Derien agrees. &quot;Maybe we wouldn't have needed to revise quite that much, don't you think?&quot;

&quot;But it paid off,&quot; I point out. &quot;I bet you had no trouble with the history exam, either?&quot;

&quot;Not really, though I think I might've messed up a few years in that question about the Black Stone War and the invasion. I think you had a hoot with the Master, though?&quot;

I grin. The history teacher always arranges someone to watch over the class during the exams so I can take the same thing orally with him while they're at it. &quot;I did. In the end we had to take the last two questions pretty quick, because we got totally carried away while discussing the second and third century expansion politics.&quot;

Derien laughs aloud. &quot;You shouldn't be left alone in the same room with him, you're both such geeks!&quot; 

&quot;So what? I think you just envy me because I'm the only one in class who actually likes exams!&quot; 

&quot;Of course I do, it's totally unfair that anyone should like exams,&quot; Derien says. He's trying to sound insulted but not succeeding too well. &quot;It should be prohibited by law or something.&quot;

&quot;It's just because I have fewer exams than the rest of you,&quot; I remind him. &quot;Must make the most of what I can do.&quot;

&quot;Okay, okay. Shall I come to your place to do homework, or what?&quot;

&quot;Please do, unless it's too difficult when there's no writing desk.&quot;

&quot;Bah, I'll just do those things that require writing after I go home. What about your essay, though?&quot;

&quot;It's only for Friday. I want to think about it first.&quot;

We wall ourselves up in my room and attack the homework, buoyed by sandwiches that Mum carries up on a small tray. Unusually, I'm having some trouble concentrating and I know why: the term is nearly at an end, summer break is going to start soon and that means &ndash; what? No school, at any rate, but what about the rest? Am I going to meet the classmates when we're not spending several hours of every day in the same place? And what about Derien? I know he's probably going to work at least part-time, as are quite a few others. They're likely to be too busy to come and see me at home, and what am I going to do then? 

When Derien has left once again, I sit for a long time in the armchair in my room and try to drive away the gloom that clings to me like a wet blanket. Birds are singing outside, the air already smells so summery and I should be overjoyed like everyone else. To me summer now means something very different, though, than to the rest of them. To all of us it means a break in the routine, but where everyone else is looking forward to it, I dread the change. Before this, summer has meant more time for Derien to be with me, now things are going to be different, and there's the girl, too. The girl he likes. 

At dinner, Mum and Dad ask what's wrong with me but I lie to them that I'm just tired. There's too much to think about. One thing especially keeps me awake until late at night after we've all retired and crawled to bed, and I can't help wishing it had never occurred to me: everything else aside, this one question has suddenly decided to loom large in my mind. I don't think I've ever really thought about it before, now it doesn't want to go away at all after I've been made aware that there might be a problem. 

Most of my classmates will be working during the summer, at least part-time. Some of them have already had little jobs before, some with their parents or relatives, others working in companies or shops or workshops. Some of them even say that they're going to go on in those jobs after they finish school, some are going to study and learn more about something they've got to try out when working. They have goals. They are going to find a job and earn their living.

What about me? What am I going to live on? There are my parents, yes, but. Doesn't that mean that even if they live until a very great age, I'll be forever dependent on them &ndash; and I don't need to think very long to know that I don't want that. 

Oh, I know that I'll be forever dependent on others at least to some extent, but I can't bear the thought that this'd be all there is to life. Surely there must be something I can do, some kind of work where my blindness wouldn't be an impossible obstacle? Also, the past few months in school have shown that I love being around people, love it even more than I realized before. I want to live, I want to experience things and I want to do that without my parents around. I wish I could say why the thought makes me feel so suffocating, but it does. 

The same things go round and round in my head until at some point I fall asleep at last, fuzzily knowing that I'm going to be damn tired in the morning. 

